history.content:
So next semester, it looks like Denis Auroux and Edward Frenkel are teaching.

I don't know too much about Auroux, but he did teach at MIT and you can find his MV calc lectures on open course ware.  He is very good, and it seems according to people online, he is not too hard either.

Frenkel is pretty straightforward.  He doesn't collect homework, although you should still do them.  And the exams are not bad at all, very similar to homework problems (I think some are almost identical in fact).  GSI's will determine quiz difficulty.

If you take Frenkel, pretty much no time commitment if you don't do all the homework, but either should be manageable.

children.subject: Depends on whether are you good at geometry. For me, MATH 53 is wayyy harder than MATH 54, and even harder than CS 70 since I am really poor at geometry.

history.content: How hard/how much time does Math 53 take? I'm planning to take it next semester along CS188, CS61C, EE16B, and possibly another CS upper div. For reference, I'm taking Math 110 this semester and I would say it is moderate difficulty.
